entry.content:
When the App-to-app link capturing flag for Workspace apps is enabled,

Workspace apps will now capture links in Workspace app windows, even if

other apps are candidates. This behavior can be overridden by enabling

the link capturing preference for the other app.



This is useful for allowing the Workspace app group to default link

capture even while conflicting apps (e.g. ARC Workspace apps) are

installed.

entry.title: Revert "[views] Ensure modal constrained windows are visible on-screen"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 6b88ed9df49b816059a7ef0eaa34f67f0ce9ea9e.



Reason for revert: Suspect for recent increase in failure rate on mac



First failing build: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/mac64/136515/overview



https://ci.chromium.org/ui/test/chrome/ninja%3A%2F%2Fchrome%2Ftest%3Ainteractive_ui_tests%2FDetachToBrowserTabDragControllerTest.DetachToOwnWindowWithDialog%2FTabDragging.0?q=VHASH%3A328d4df66334edf6



Original change's description:

> [views] Ensure modal constrained windows are visible on-screen

>

> This CL updates UpdateModalDialogPosition() code to ensure

> constrained dialogs and their parent windows remain visible

> when shown.

>

> The modal dialog may not be user-visible in the case where

> 1. The transient parent is not visible on-screen

> 2. The dialog was repositioned outside the bounds of its

> transient parent.

>

> Many platforms will clip transient children to the bounds of

> the parent so it is necessary that the constrained window

> remain within the bounds of the parent to avoid rendering the

> window unresponsive when dialog controls become inaccessible.

>

> In the case the transient parent itself is partially or

> completely off-screen it is necessary to reposition it back

> into the screen's user-visible work area. This is necessary

> as otherwise the dialog may end up positioned off-screen

> similarly makes the dialog controls inaccessible and

> renders the window unresponsive.

>

the call slightly later in the browser process startup to just after

the check for the process singleton. This should not impact dark mode

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Adds flag to pretend all suggestions are defaultable
entry.content:
When enabled, all matches set `allowed_to_be_default_match` to true.

Traditionally, few matches are allowed to be default:

- Trivial URL/search what you typed matches

- Searches prefixed by the input

- URLs prefixed by the input

- Shortcut texts prefixed by the input



This limitation is due to the cost (both in terms of implementation and

simplicity and readability for the user) of upgrading the UI to support

inlining more texts. So we have a chicken-and-egg problem, we don't want

to invest in the UI until we know lifting this limitation will improve

ranking greatly; we won't know if ranking will benefit greatly unless we

run experiments; we can't run experiments unless we fix the UI.



This CL adds a flag to lift the limitation without fixing the UI or

covering all edge cases. It's not launchable or experimentable. But

maybe by dogfooding it we can estimate both a) how beneficial is this to

ranking, and b) what we need to address to make this launchable.

entry.title: blink: Reset EventListenerProperties when swapping delegate.
entry.content:
Tearing down the layout tree resets state on the compositor for event

handlers tied to the layout objects. This happens implicitly when the

layout tree is destroyed for a cross-document navigation.



With RenderDocument, the compositor has already been detached when the

tear down occurs. Safely avoid resetting state on the compositor for

this case.



In order to avoid a behaviour change, also reset this state when the

compositor is swapped to the new widget. In effect, instead of the

state being reset during old Document tear down, it gets reset earlier

when the compositor is passed between widgets.

entry.title: HTTPS-First Mode: Move Typically Secure User heuristic checks to startup
entry.content:
This CL modifies the Typically Secure User heuristic in a few ways:

- The heuristic no longer auto-enables HTTPS-First Mode during or after

a navigation. This is now only done on startup.

- It now records a timestamp when the heuristic starts observing the

profile for the first time. This timestamp is then used to compute the

observation duration. If the heuristic hasn't observed the profile for

at least a week, it won't auto-enable HTTPS-First Mode.

- The heuristic will not auto-enable HTTPS-First Mode if the most

recent fallback entry is less than a day ago. This gives us more time

to observe new fallback entries and decide whether the browsing pattern

is typically secure.

entry.content:
animations have ended



We added a PostTask in crrev.com/c/4878237 to clear a strip tab hover

state on an ACTION_DOWN event on the strip. However, this is not

reliably working because we are seeing issues with the card

sticking/showing undesirably on tab closure/tab reordering (refer to the

discussion on the linked bug).



This CL adds a more reliable solution to clear the tab hover state after

any animations triggered by actions (like tab closure, tab selection,

tab reordering) on the strip have ended. The CL also adds an update to

avoid applying the hover state while such animations are in progress.
